{"questionId":"9067061","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Physical properties of elements vary according to atomic number. Sections 6 to 9 of the data booklet list some of these properties.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/43377c5a69c579d225b752a8574152b5900dd137.png\" width=\"753\" height=\"519\"></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Describe the density trend across periods 4 and 5 of the periodic table.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/95aef47f33449b672ce7c1771c62c8f273c37a9d.png\" width=\"710\" height=\"300\"></span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">density increases «to a maximum in the transition elements» <em><strong>AND</strong> </em>then decreases&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9067061","referenceCode":"19M.3.sl.TZ1.b(i)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Describe the density trend across periods 4 and 5 of the periodic table.","paper":"3","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b(i)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 11: Measurement and data processing","11.2 Graphical techniques","Core","Topic 11: Measurement and data processing"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}